<font color="#FF0000">FOR YOUR EYES ONLY</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 13  0:15:06 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
A reported asked me once, &quot;How do you get medals?&quot;  My response to her was, &quot;It's like a speeding ticket ...everybody speeds... but not everybody gets written up!<br>
It is safe to say that the awarding of military decorations is not standardized between the lower ranks and the higher ranks... between units... between branches of service... and not even between MOSs.  Combat infantrymen (Army) often received Air Medals for doing combat assaults in helicopters.  I have no problem with that.  I did not receive a Combat Infantryman's Badge because I did not have the right MOS.  I'd give a five gallon can full of Air Medals for one CIB, to me the most prestigious decoration of all!<br>
I was reported KIA... my records were closed, I was reported MIA on two occassions... my records were closed... I was medivaced to Camp Zama, Japan... and my records were closed. I was decorated in 1990... twenty-six years late for my first tour.  I have never received anything for my second tour and may never.<br>
In 1966, it was a little bit more hush - hush to go into Laos or Cambodia.   The operation that I was on, Operation Omega was very secret, Top Secret Kyrpto.  I know of no decorations given...PERIOD!!<br>
Most helicopter pilots were highly decorated, even though they died or were medivaced between 30 and 170 days in country.  It was a dangerous pass time for crews and their passengers.<br>
My point was not to infuriate or impress anyone with my exposure to combat situations.  I simply wanted to emphasize that felt more reward from someone that I had rescued than all the medals in the world including our highest.  Too, I wanted to express a little anger in being devaluated by a lying government who lied to us over there and to the people back in the United States.<br>
I went to Vietnam the first time to &quot;help&quot; the Vietnamese people and &quot;free&quot; people worldwide.  The second time, I went to help American fighting men.  I did the best I could at both endeavors because of internal values and not for medals.  I was decorated as a Warrant Officer One and as a Second Lieutenant, not as a Colonel or a politician.  I am not ashamed of my decorations.  I wear them when I am asked to speak at Military and Veteran functions because people ask me to!<br>
I have been married for a year.  Last Christmas, my wife, a Dutch citizen, dug all my medals out of shoe boxes, dresser drawers, closets and the attic and with the help of my brother, &quot;Toon Sarge,&quot; she mounted them in a shadow box.<br>
I am not know for being overly modest... but waiting thirty one years to hand them on the wall ain't to bad!<br>
The greatest things left from the Viet Nam War, and the only things of value, are the veterans who are my friends.<br>
Those of you who I have offended can kiss my ass.  Those of you who are impressed can drop and give me twenty...the rest, like Doc Del and Silent Warrior... can just move on like the rest of us!<br><br>
Mustang Two Four<br><br>

